    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-03-25T13:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-03-25T13:30:00-05:00" n="165"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d165">
                <head>165. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_BWG1" type="from">William G.
                        Bowdler</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to President
                        <persName corresp="#p_JLB1" type="to">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d165fn1">Source: <persName>Johnson</persName>
                        Library, National Security File, Memos to the President, <persName
                            corresp="#p_BM1">McGeorge Bundy</persName>, Vol. 21.Secret; Eyes Only.
                        An “L” on the memorandum indicates that the President saw it. A copy was
                        sent to Bill Moyers.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1966-03-25T13:30:00-05:00">March 25, 1966, 1:30 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Preliminary Read out of Dominican Poll</item>
                </list>
                <p>The preliminary results of the February–March poll in the Dominican Republic show
                    few differences with the November poll, and the differences which do occur do
                    not affect the standing of the main candidates.</p>
                <list>
                    <item>—<persName corresp="#p_BJ1">Balaguer</persName> still leads <persName
                            corresp="#p_BJ4">Bosch</persName> by better than 2 to 1 (50.4% to 21%).
                        This represents a drop of .6% for <persName corresp="#p_BJ1"
                            >Balaguer</persName> from the November poll and 1.0% for <persName
                            corresp="#p_BJ4">Bosch</persName>.</item>
                    <item>—In party strength, <persName corresp="#p_BJ1">Balaguer</persName>ʼs
                            <gloss target="#t_PR1">PR</gloss> party leads <persName corresp="#p_BJ4"
                            >Bosch</persName>ʼs <gloss target="#t_PRD1">PRD</gloss> party by 41.6%
                        to 21.6%. This represents a drop of 0.6% for the <gloss target="#t_PR1"
                            >PR</gloss> from the November poll and 7.4% for the <gloss
                            target="#t_PRD1">PRD</gloss>.</item>
                    <item>—On the issue of our military intervention, 63.2% of the Dominicans
                        continue to think that it helped. In November the figure was 65%.</item>
                    <item>—On the <gloss target="#t_IAPF1">IAPF</gloss> departing, 46.1% of the
                        people now think that the Force should stay beyond elections, an increase of
                        7.5% over the November poll.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Two important factors must be borne in mind in assessing the figures on the
                    candidates and their parties: <list>
                        <item>—The poll does <hi rend="italic">not</hi> cover a period when
                                <persName corresp="#p_BJ4">Bosch</persName> was actively
                            campaigning—and he is a formidable campaigner.</item>
                        <pb facs="0417" n="382" xml:id="pg_382"/>
                        <item>—The pollʼs percentages are based on the assumption that the
                            population of <hi rend="italic">actual</hi> voters does not differ
                            significantly from the population of <hi rend="italic">eligible</hi>
                                voters.<note n="2" xml:id="d165fn2">Komer commented on this p <gloss
                                    target="#t_ARA1">ARA</gloss> graph and wrote the following note
                                at the bottom of the page: “Iʼm asking <persName corresp="#p_BWG1"
                                    >Bowdler</persName> to look at pros and cons of surfacing
                                this.”</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Alarge voter turnout—particularly in rural areas where <persName corresp="#p_BJ1"
                        >Balaguer</persName>ʼs strength is concentrated—is essential to <persName
                        corresp="#p_BJ1">Balaguer</persName>ʼs chances.<gloss target="#t_CIA1"
                        >CIA</gloss>, State, <persName corresp="#p_BE1">Bunker</persName> and the
                    Embassy are keenly aware of this and know that a substantial portion of their
                    homework lies in this direction. I am satisfied that they are hard at it, and
                        <persName corresp="#p_GGH1">Garcia Godoy</persName> is cooperating fully.
                    But a reminder by you to <persName corresp="#p_BE1">Ellsworth</persName> when
                    you next see him would not be amiss.</p>
                <p>A copy of the [<hi rend="italic">less than 1 line of source text not
                        declassified</hi>] report is attached.<note n="3" xml:id="d165fn3">Attached
                        but not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWG1">
                            <hi rend="strong">WGB</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
